export const questionBank17 = [
  {q:"A company hosts a web application on EC2 instances behind an ALB. They want to authenticate users at the ALB level before requests reach the application. Users are in a corporate Okta directory. What ALB feature supports this?", opts:["ALB does not support authentication","ALB built-in authentication — supports OpenID Connect (OIDC) providers like Okta, Cognito, or any OIDC-compliant IdP directly at the load balancer layer","WAF rules for authentication","Lambda@Edge for authentication"], correct:1, exp:"ALB has built-in authentication support via listener rules. Configure an 'authenticate-oidc' action that redirects unauthenticated users to the IdP (Okta) login page. After authentication, the IdP redirects back to ALB with a token. ALB validates the token and forwards the request to the target with user claims in headers. No application code changes needed. Supports Cognito User Pools and any OIDC provider (Okta, Auth0, Azure AD).", domain:1},
  {q:"A company stores sensitive documents in S3. Compliance requires that objects CANNOT be deleted or overwritten for 7 years after creation, even by the root account. Which feature enforces this?", opts:["S3 Versioning with MFA Delete","S3 Object Lock in Compliance mode with 7-year retention period (nobody, including root, can delete before retention expires)","S3 Bucket Policy denying delete actions","S3 Glacier Vault Lock"], correct:1, exp:"S3 Object Lock Compliance mode makes objects immutable for the retention period. Unlike Governance mode (which allows users with special permissions to override), Compliance mode CANNOT be overridden by anyone — including the root user or AWS support. Objects cannot be deleted or overwritten until the retention period expires. This meets SEC 17a-4, FINRA, and other regulatory requirements for immutable storage.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFormation and needs to perform a complex operation that CloudFormation doesn't natively support (e.g., emptying an S3 bucket before stack deletion). What CloudFormation feature allows custom logic?", opts:["CloudFormation Hooks (validate, not execute)","Custom Resources backed by Lambda — CloudFormation invokes a Lambda function during create/update/delete, and the function performs custom logic","CloudFormation Macros (template transformation, not execution logic)","CloudFormation StackSets"], correct:1, exp:"Custom Resources (AWS::CloudFormation::CustomResource or Custom::*) allow you to execute arbitrary logic during stack operations. CloudFormation sends a request to a Lambda function (or SNS topic) with the request type (Create/Update/Delete). The Lambda performs custom logic (empty bucket, configure third-party service, etc.) and signals success/failure back to CloudFormation. Essential for operations outside CloudFormation's native capabilities.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company needs to migrate 500 virtual machines from VMware vSphere to AWS EC2. They want to minimize downtime and track migration progress centrally. Which service automates this?", opts:["AWS Server Migration Service (SMS) — deprecated","AWS Application Migration Service (MGN) — continuous replication with minimal downtime cutover, centralized dashboard for tracking 500 VMs","Import VM images manually using EC2 Import/Export","Recreate all VMs from scratch on EC2"], correct:1, exp:"AWS MGN (Application Migration Service) replaces the deprecated SMS. It provides: continuous block-level replication (minimal cutover downtime — minutes, not hours), automated conversion from VMware to EC2, centralized dashboard tracking all 500 VMs migration status, and non-disruptive testing. The replication agent continuously syncs changes. During cutover, final sync + launch takes minutes. This is THE service for large-scale VM-to-EC2 migrations.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon EMR for big data processing (Spark jobs). Jobs run for 2-4 hours and are fault-tolerant (can retry failed tasks). They want to reduce costs by 60%. Which instance purchasing option for the task nodes?", opts:["On-Demand for all nodes","Spot Instances for task nodes (up to 90% cheaper, acceptable for fault-tolerant batch processing). Keep master and core nodes On-Demand for stability.","Reserved Instances for all nodes","Savings Plans for task nodes"], correct:1, exp:"EMR architecture: Master node (job coordination — must be stable), Core nodes (HDFS storage + processing — should be stable), Task nodes (processing only — can be terminated without data loss). Spot Instances for task nodes: 60-90% cost savings, and if Spot is reclaimed, EMR retries the task on another instance. Master and core nodes should use On-Demand (or On-Demand for master, mix for core). This is the standard EMR cost optimization pattern.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company has an application that writes 50,000 records per second to DynamoDB. Each record is 1KB. The table uses provisioned capacity. What Write Capacity Units (WCU) are needed?", opts:["50,000 WCU (1 WCU = 1KB write per second)","25,000 WCU (1 WCU = 2KB writes per second)","5,000 WCU (1 WCU = 10KB writes per second)","100,000 WCU (need buffer for overhead)"], correct:0, exp:"DynamoDB WCU calculation: 1 WCU = 1 write per second for items up to 1KB. For items larger than 1KB, round up (e.g., 2.5KB item = 3 WCU per write). With 50,000 writes/sec of 1KB items: 50,000 × 1 = 50,000 WCU needed. For eventually consistent writes (not applicable — writes are always strongly consistent in DynamoDB), the formula doesn't change. Read Capacity Units (RCU): 1 RCU = 1 strongly consistent read/sec for items up to 4KB.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company needs to collect and analyze VPC network traffic metadata (source/destination IPs, ports, protocols, packet counts, bytes). They DON'T need packet payload inspection. Which feature provides this?", opts:["VPC Traffic Mirroring (copies full packets — more than needed and expensive)","VPC Flow Logs (captures network flow metadata: source/dest IP, port, protocol, packets, bytes, action ACCEPT/REJECT per ENI)","AWS Network Firewall (filters traffic, doesn't log metadata by default)","CloudWatch Network Monitoring"], correct:1, exp:"VPC Flow Logs capture IP traffic metadata going to/from network interfaces (ENIs). Each record: timestamp, source IP, dest IP, source port, dest port, protocol, packets, bytes, action (ACCEPT/REJECT). Publish to: CloudWatch Logs, S3, or Kinesis Data Firehose. Query with Athena (from S3) or CloudWatch Insights. Does NOT capture packet contents (payload). Traffic Mirroring copies full packets — overkill for metadata-only analysis and costly.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses S3 for a data lake. They need to provide SQL query access to analysts who are familiar with standard SQL but NOT AWS tools. What is the simplest way to query S3 data with SQL?", opts:["Set up a Redshift cluster and load data from S3","Amazon Athena — serverless SQL queries directly on S3 data (no infrastructure to manage, pay per query, standard SQL)","Set up Apache Hive on EMR","RDS with data loaded from S3"], correct:1, exp:"Athena: serverless, instant setup, standard SQL (Presto/Trino engine), queries S3 data directly without loading into a database. Analysts write SQL in the console or connect via JDBC/ODBC. Pay $5 per TB scanned. Supports CSV, JSON, Parquet, ORC, Avro. Uses Glue Data Catalog for schema. No infrastructure to manage. Redshift works but requires cluster management. EMR requires Hadoop expertise. Athena is the simplest SQL-over-S3 solution.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses ECS on Fargate. They want to configure their tasks to allocate 2 vCPU and 8GB memory. But Fargate rejects the task definition. Why?", opts:["Fargate doesn't support that much memory","Fargate has specific valid CPU/memory combinations — 2 vCPU supports 4GB to 16GB memory (8GB is valid). Check if the value format is correct (memory must be in MiB: 8192, not '8GB')","Fargate has a maximum of 1 vCPU","ECS doesn't support Fargate"], correct:1, exp:"Fargate has specific valid CPU/memory combinations. For 2 vCPU (2048 CPU units): memory must be between 4096-16384 MiB (4-16GB in 1GB increments). Common mistake: specifying memory as '8GB' instead of '8192' (MiB integer). Also: CPU must be specified in CPU units (256, 512, 1024, 2048, 4096), memory in MiB. 2vCPU + 8GB (8192 MiB) IS a valid combination — the issue is likely the format, not the values.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Cognito for user authentication in their mobile app. They want to give authenticated users direct access to AWS resources (specifically their own folder in S3). What Cognito feature provides AWS credentials?", opts:["Cognito User Pools directly provide AWS credentials","Cognito Identity Pools (Federated Identities) — exchanges user pool tokens for temporary AWS credentials with IAM role-based permissions","IAM users per app user (doesn't scale)","S3 pre-signed URLs generated by the backend (alternative approach)"], correct:1, exp:"Flow: User authenticates with Cognito User Pool → receives JWT tokens → exchanges token with Cognito Identity Pool → receives temporary AWS credentials (STS) → uses credentials to access S3 directly. The Identity Pool maps authenticated users to an IAM role. Using IAM policy variables (${cognito-identity.amazonaws.com:sub}), each user can access ONLY their own S3 prefix. This enables secure, direct mobile-to-S3 access without a backend proxy.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs a cron job at midnight that processes all orders from the day. The job queries RDS for ~1 million rows, performs calculations, and writes results back. During processing, the production database becomes slow. What is the BEST architectural improvement?", opts:["Run the cron job at 3 AM instead (still impacts production, just different time)","Read from a Read Replica for the query portion, write results to the primary (separates read load from production transactions)","Export daily data to S3 and process with Lambda/Batch, write results back to RDS via a separate connection","Increase RDS instance size to handle both workloads"], correct:1, exp:"A Read Replica isolates the heavy analytical read from the primary. The cron job: reads 1M rows from the replica (no impact on primary) → performs calculations → writes results to primary (smaller write operation). The primary only handles the final writes, not the massive read scan. This is the standard OLTP/analytics separation pattern. S3 + Batch also works but adds complexity. The Read Replica approach requires minimal code changes.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses CloudWatch metrics to monitor their application. They publish a custom metric every 60 seconds. They want an alarm that triggers if the metric is missing for 5 minutes (the application stopped reporting). What alarm configuration detects missing data?", opts:["Set alarm threshold to 0","Configure the alarm to treat missing data as 'breaching' — when 5 consecutive periods have no data, the alarm enters ALARM state","Use a composite alarm checking for data presence","CloudWatch can't detect missing metrics"], correct:1, exp:"CloudWatch Alarms have a 'Treat missing data as' setting: 'missing' (maintain current state), 'notBreaching' (treat as OK), 'breaching' (treat as ALARM), 'ignore' (don't evaluate). Setting to 'breaching' means: if the metric reports nothing for the evaluation periods, CloudWatch treats it as threshold-breaching → ALARM. This detects applications that stopped sending metrics. Critical for monitoring agent health, heartbeats, and application liveness.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company has a Lambda function (Python) with a deployment package of 200MB (including ML model). Lambda's deployment package limit is 250MB (unzipped). They need to add more dependencies, pushing over 250MB. What are their options?", opts:["Lambda has a hard 250MB limit — no workaround","Use a Lambda Container Image (up to 10GB image size) — package the function, model, and all dependencies in a Docker container deployed to Lambda","Split the function into multiple smaller Lambdas","Remove the ML model and download from S3 at runtime (adds latency)"], correct:1, exp:"Lambda Container Image support allows deployment packages up to 10GB. Package your Python code, ML model, and all dependencies in a Docker image, push to ECR, and configure the Lambda to use the container image. Same Lambda features (invocation, scaling, pricing) with much larger package support. The 250MB limit only applies to .zip deployment packages. Container images solve the size limitation while maintaining the serverless execution model.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Secrets Manager to store database credentials. They enable automatic rotation every 30 days. The rotation uses a Lambda function. After rotation, some applications fail to connect. What is the recommended rotation strategy to prevent this?", opts:["Single-user rotation (changes password of the single user — risky if apps cache old password)","Alternating users rotation strategy — maintains TWO database users (userA and userB). Rotation alternates the active user, so the previous credentials remain valid during transition.","Don't use automatic rotation — rotate manually during maintenance windows","Extend the rotation period to 90 days"], correct:1, exp:"Alternating users strategy: Secrets Manager maintains two database users and alternates between them. When rotating: creates/updates the inactive user's password, updates the secret to point to the newly-active user. The previously-active user's credentials remain valid briefly (for apps that cached them). This eliminates the window where applications hold stale credentials. Single-user rotation changes the password instantly — apps with cached credentials fail.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company needs to deploy the same CloudFormation stack to 100 AWS accounts across 5 regions simultaneously. What is the MOST efficient approach?", opts:["Run the template manually in each account/region","CloudFormation StackSets — deploy a single template across multiple accounts and regions in one operation, with automatic retry and drift detection","Write a script that uses the CLI to create stacks in each account","Use Terraform with multiple provider configurations"], correct:1, exp:"CloudFormation StackSets deploy a template across multiple target accounts AND regions from a single management account. Features: parallel deployment, per-region deployment order control, automatic retries, drift detection, and centralized management. Deploy to 100 accounts × 5 regions = 500 stack instances from one StackSet definition. Ideal for guardrails, Config rules, IAM roles, or any standardized resource across an Organization.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses an S3 bucket for hosting a static website (bucket website endpoint). They enable HTTPS via CloudFront. However, they notice that users can still access the S3 website endpoint directly over HTTP (bypassing CloudFront). How do they force all access through CloudFront?", opts:["Disable S3 static website hosting (use S3 REST endpoint instead) and use Origin Access Control (OAC) to restrict S3 access to CloudFront only","Add a bucket policy denying all requests except those from CloudFront IP ranges","Use WAF on the S3 bucket (not possible — WAF attaches to CloudFront/ALB)","Enable S3 Block Public Access (breaks website hosting)"], correct:0, exp:"S3 website endpoints don't support OAC/OAI — they require public access. Solution: DON'T use the S3 website endpoint. Instead: use the S3 REST endpoint as the CloudFront origin + OAC. OAC allows ONLY CloudFront to access the S3 bucket. The bucket is no longer publicly accessible. For SPA routing (404 handling), configure CloudFront custom error responses. This eliminates direct S3 access while maintaining website functionality through CloudFront.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company runs Lambda functions that interact with RDS in a VPC. They need the Lambda to also access DynamoDB and S3 (which are outside the VPC). What is needed?", opts:["Lambda can't access both VPC resources and AWS services simultaneously","Lambda in VPC needs VPC Endpoints (Gateway Endpoint for S3, Interface Endpoint for DynamoDB) OR a NAT Gateway for internet/AWS service access","Move RDS outside the VPC (not possible)","Use VPC Peering between Lambda VPC and the AWS services VPC (not how it works)"], correct:1, exp:"Lambda in a VPC has no internet access by default. To reach AWS services (DynamoDB, S3, etc.): Option 1: VPC Endpoints (Gateway for S3/DynamoDB — free, Interface for other services — small hourly cost). Option 2: NAT Gateway in a public subnet (costs more, provides full internet access). VPC Endpoints are preferred for AWS services (private, free/cheaper). NAT Gateway needed only if Lambda must reach the public internet.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon SES (Simple Email Service) to send transactional emails (order confirmations, password resets). They notice a high bounce rate and their sending reputation is declining. What should they implement?", opts:["Send more emails to improve reputation (opposite of correct)","Implement SES configuration sets with bounce/complaint handling — automatically suppress hard-bounced emails, process complaint feedback loops, and monitor reputation dashboard","Switch to a third-party email provider","Add all recipients to a suppression list"], correct:1, exp:"SES reputation management: (1) Configuration sets track bounces, complaints, and deliveries. (2) Account-level suppression list automatically prevents re-sending to hard-bounced addresses. (3) Process complaint feedback (ISPs forward complaints when users mark email as spam) — remove those addresses. (4) Monitor the reputation dashboard (bounce rate <5%, complaint rate <0.1%). Continuing to send to bad addresses destroys sending reputation and can result in account suspension.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFront with an Application Load Balancer origin. They want to ensure the ALB ONLY accepts requests from CloudFront (not direct access). What is the recommended approach?", opts:["Restrict ALB Security Group to CloudFront IP ranges (maintained by AWS in a prefix list, but list changes frequently)","Add a custom header in CloudFront origin settings and configure ALB rules to only accept requests containing that header","Use AWS WAF on the ALB to verify a CloudFront-specific header","Both B and C — custom header verification is the recommended approach, implementable via ALB rules or WAF"], correct:3, exp:"Recommended approach: (1) Configure CloudFront to add a custom secret header (X-Custom-Header: random-secret-value) in the origin custom headers. (2) ALB listener rule verifies the header — rejects requests without it. This works because clients can't know the secret header value. Alternative: AWS WAF rule on ALB checking the header. Both prevent direct ALB access. Security Group restriction to CloudFront IPs works but the IP list changes and requires maintenance.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company needs to process CSV files uploaded to S3. Each file is 5MB and contains 100,000 rows. They need to validate each row, transform it, and load into DynamoDB. Files arrive at 10/minute during business hours. Which architecture is MOST serverless and cost-effective?", opts:["EC2 instance polling S3 for new files","S3 Event Notification → Lambda function (processes each file: validates rows, transforms, batch-writes to DynamoDB using BatchWriteItem)","S3 → SQS → ECS Fargate task per file","AWS Glue ETL job triggered by each file upload"], correct:1, exp:"Lambda is ideal: triggered by S3 event (serverless), processes 5MB file easily within 15-minute limit, validates/transforms rows in memory, and batch-writes to DynamoDB (25 items per BatchWriteItem). 10 files/minute = 10 concurrent Lambda invocations — well within limits. Cost: only pay for actual compute time. ECS Fargate has minimum charge per task (1 minute). Glue has 10-minute minimum billing and higher cost for small jobs. Lambda is the sweet spot for this workload size.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Transit Gateway to connect 20 VPCs. They notice that VPC A can route to VPC B, but VPC B cannot initiate connections back to VPC A. Routing tables in both VPCs have the correct entries. What is likely the issue?", opts:["Transit Gateway doesn't support bidirectional communication","The Transit Gateway route table is missing a route for VPC B → VPC A. Check the TGW route table associations and propagations for both VPC attachments.","Security Groups are blocking return traffic","NACLs are stateful and should allow return traffic automatically (NACLs are stateless)"], correct:1, exp:"Transit Gateway uses its OWN route tables (separate from VPC route tables). Each VPC attachment is associated with a TGW route table AND propagates its routes to TGW route tables. If VPC B's CIDR is not in the TGW route table that VPC A's attachment uses (or vice versa), routing fails in one direction. Check: TGW route table associations (which table does each attachment use?) and propagations (which CIDRs are propagated?). Both directions must have routes.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company wants to implement a disaster recovery strategy with RPO of 1 hour and RTO of 4 hours. Their production runs in us-east-1 with RDS, EC2 Auto Scaling, and S3. What is the MOST cost-effective DR strategy?", opts:["Multi-site active/active (overkill for 4-hour RTO — very expensive)","Pilot Light — minimal resources running in DR region (RDS read replica, AMIs ready, S3 replication). Scale up during disaster.","Warm Standby — scaled-down but running infrastructure in DR region","Backup and Restore — periodic backups to DR region, restore from scratch during disaster"], correct:1, exp:"With RPO=1 hour and RTO=4 hours: Pilot Light is optimal. Keep running: RDS Read Replica (continuous replication — RPO near zero), S3 Cross-Region Replication (RPO < 15 min). Keep ready: current AMIs, launch templates, CloudFormation templates. During disaster: promote RDS replica, launch EC2 from templates, update DNS. 4-hour RTO allows time to provision. Warm Standby (always-running scaled-down infra) is unnecessary expense for 4-hour RTO. Backup/Restore risks exceeding 4-hour RTO for complex environments.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses DynamoDB Streams to capture table changes and process them with Lambda. They need to send each change to both an SQS queue AND an SNS topic. Lambda currently processes changes one at a time. What pattern enables fan-out?", opts:["Two Lambda functions on the same DynamoDB Stream (only ONE Lambda consumer per stream shard)","DynamoDB Streams → Lambda → publishes to SNS topic (which has both SQS queue and other subscribers as subscriptions). SNS fans out to multiple subscribers.","DynamoDB Streams → EventBridge Pipes → multiple destinations","Both B and C work — SNS fan-out is the classic pattern, EventBridge Pipes is newer and more flexible"], correct:3, exp:"Classic pattern: DynamoDB Streams → Lambda → SNS topic → (SQS queue subscription + other subscribers). Lambda reads stream and publishes to SNS, which fans out to all subscribers. Newer: EventBridge Pipes can read from DynamoDB Streams and route to multiple targets with filtering/enrichment. Both achieve the fan-out requirement. SNS fan-out is well-established and simple. EventBridge Pipes adds filtering, transformation, and direct integration without custom Lambda code.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company has a 100GB PostgreSQL database that they want to migrate to Aurora PostgreSQL with MINIMAL downtime. They can tolerate a 5-minute cutover window. What migration approach?", opts:["pg_dump/pg_restore (requires full downtime during dump + restore — hours for 100GB)","AWS DMS with full load + CDC (Change Data Capture) — full initial load while source stays live, then continuous replication catches up. Cutover: stop writes, wait for DMS to sync, switch to Aurora (~5 min).","Aurora clone from an RDS PostgreSQL snapshot (only works if already on RDS)","AWS SCT for the full migration"], correct:1, exp:"DMS with full load + CDC: (1) Full load copies the 100GB to Aurora while the source database continues serving traffic. (2) CDC continuously replicates changes made after the full load started. (3) When replication lag is near zero, perform cutover: stop application writes to source, wait for DMS to apply final changes (seconds), switch application to Aurora. Total downtime: ~5 minutes. pg_dump requires full downtime (hours). This is THE minimal-downtime database migration pattern.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses S3 with versioning enabled. They accidentally uploaded a 100GB file that they don't need. They delete it, but their storage bill doesn't decrease. Why?", opts:["S3 bills hourly, not daily — wait for the billing cycle","Deleting a versioned object adds a DELETE MARKER but doesn't remove previous versions — the 100GB object version still exists and is billed. Must explicitly delete the version ID to permanently remove it.","S3 has minimum storage duration charges","The file is in a lifecycle transition and can't be deleted"], correct:1, exp:"With S3 Versioning enabled, 'deleting' an object only adds a delete marker (hides the object from listings). All previous versions remain stored and BILLED. To truly free storage: delete the specific version (using version ID) or configure a lifecycle rule to expire non-current versions after N days. This is a common surprise with versioned buckets — 'deleted' objects continue consuming storage. Use S3 Inventory to find old versions consuming storage.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company needs their Lambda function to call a third-party HTTPS API. The function is in a VPC (to access RDS). The third-party API is on the public internet. How does the Lambda reach it?", opts:["Lambda in VPC can't access the internet","Configure a NAT Gateway in a public subnet of the VPC, add a route 0.0.0.0/0 → NAT Gateway in the Lambda's private subnet route table","Add an Internet Gateway route to the Lambda's subnet (makes it public — security risk and Lambda ENIs don't get public IPs anyway)","Use a VPC endpoint for the third-party API (only works for AWS services and PrivateLink partners)"], correct:1, exp:"Lambda in a VPC uses ENIs in private subnets. For internet access: add a NAT Gateway in a public subnet (which has IGW route), then route 0.0.0.0/0 → NAT GW in the private subnet's route table. Lambda's outbound traffic flows: Lambda ENI → NAT Gateway → IGW → Internet. VPC endpoints don't work for arbitrary third-party APIs. Lambda ENIs never receive public IPs, so adding them to a public subnet with IGW route doesn't help.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Backup for centralized backup management. They want to ensure backup policies are applied consistently across all accounts in their AWS Organization. What feature enables this?", opts:["Create backup plans in each account individually","AWS Backup with delegated administrator — create backup policies in the management account that automatically apply to all member accounts via Organizations","Share backup vaults across accounts","Use CloudFormation StackSets to deploy backup plans"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Backup integrates with AWS Organizations. Enable backup policies at the Organization level — they automatically apply to all member accounts (or specific OUs). Accounts can't override or opt out. This ensures consistent backup schedules, retention periods, and cross-region copy rules across all accounts. Delegated administrator allows a non-management account to manage backup policies. Far more manageable than per-account configuration for large Organizations.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company runs a web application that allows users to search products. They want to implement full-text search with features like typo tolerance, faceted navigation, and relevance ranking. Current SQL LIKE queries are slow and lack features. Which AWS service?", opts:["Amazon RDS with full-text indexes (limited features)","Amazon OpenSearch Service (formerly Elasticsearch) — full-text search with relevance ranking, facets, auto-complete, fuzzy matching, and sub-second response times","Amazon Kendra (enterprise document search, overkill for product catalog)","DynamoDB with Scan and FilterExpression (terrible for search)"], correct:1, exp:"Amazon OpenSearch Service provides: full-text search with BM25/TF-IDF relevance scoring, fuzzy matching (typo tolerance), faceted navigation (filter by category/brand/price range), autocomplete suggestions, highlighting, and sub-second latency. Index your product catalog in OpenSearch, query with the full-text search DSL. It handles millions of documents with consistent low latency. Kendra is for unstructured enterprise document search (different use case).", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses RDS MySQL Multi-AZ. They want to test what happens during a failover without causing an actual outage. Can they trigger a planned failover?", opts:["No — failover only happens during unplanned events","Yes — use the 'Reboot with failover' option in the RDS console (or rds:RebootDBInstance with ForceFailover=true) to trigger a controlled failover for testing","Failover testing requires terminating the primary instance","Contact AWS Support to trigger a test failover"], correct:1, exp:"RDS allows you to trigger a planned failover by rebooting the primary instance with the 'failover' option checked. This promotes the standby to primary and demotes the old primary to standby. Use this to: test application failover handling, verify DNS resolution speed, and measure actual failover duration. The failover is controlled and recoverable. This is a standard operational practice for DR testing.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Kinesis Data Streams with 10 shards. Each shard supports 1MB/sec write and 2MB/sec read. They need to increase write capacity to 20MB/sec total. What should they do?", opts:["Increase shard size (not possible — shards have fixed capacity)","Split shards to increase from 10 to 20 shards (resharding) — doubles write capacity to 20MB/sec","Add a second Kinesis stream and load-balance writes","Increase the number of consumers (doesn't increase write capacity)"], correct:1, exp:"Kinesis shard capacity is fixed: 1MB/sec write, 2MB/sec read per shard. To increase write throughput: add shards via shard splitting (resharding). 20 shards × 1MB/sec = 20MB/sec write capacity. UpdateShardCount API scales to the target shard count. Kinesis also supports On-Demand mode which automatically scales shards based on throughput (up to 200MB/sec write). Manual resharding for provisioned mode, automatic for on-demand mode.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Control Tower to set up and govern their multi-account AWS environment. What does Control Tower provide that Organizations alone does not?", opts:["Account creation (Organizations also creates accounts)","Pre-configured guardrails (preventive SCPs + detective AWS Config rules), account factory for standardized account provisioning, landing zone with centralized logging/audit accounts, and a dashboard showing compliance status","IAM Identity Center integration (Organizations also supports this)","Consolidated billing (that's Organizations)"], correct:1, exp:"Control Tower adds on top of Organizations: (1) Landing Zone — pre-configured multi-account structure (management, log archive, audit accounts), (2) Guardrails — mandatory and elective controls (preventive SCPs + detective Config rules), (3) Account Factory — standardized account provisioning with pre-configured VPC, IAM, and guardrails, (4) Dashboard — centralized compliance view. It's the opinionated, automated setup layer that Organizations provides building blocks for.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Route 53 with a hosted zone for example.com. They want to point the apex domain (example.com — no www) to their ALB. Standard CNAME records don't work at the zone apex. What Route 53 record type should they use?", opts:["CNAME record (NOT allowed at zone apex per DNS RFC)","Alias record (Route 53 proprietary — works at zone apex, resolves ALB/CloudFront/S3 DNS names, no charge for queries)","A record with static IP (ALB IPs change)","AAAA record (IPv6 only)"], correct:1, exp:"DNS RFCs prohibit CNAME at the zone apex (conflicts with SOA/NS records). Route 53 Alias records solve this: they're an A-type record that resolves AWS resource DNS names (ALB, CloudFront, S3, API Gateway, etc.) at the zone apex. Free of charge (unlike CNAME queries). Alias records work like CNAME for resolution but are technically A/AAAA records, avoiding the RFC restriction. This is a VERY commonly tested concept.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company wants to implement a data mesh architecture on AWS. Each team owns their domain's data and publishes it as 'data products' for other teams. They need: data cataloging, access control, and cross-account data sharing. Which service enables this?", opts:["AWS Glue Data Catalog alone","AWS Lake Formation — centralized governance with fine-grained access control (column/row/cell level), cross-account data sharing, data catalog integration, and supports data mesh patterns","Amazon DataZone — purpose-built for data mesh with data portals, subscription workflows, and data product publishing","Both B and C — Lake Formation for governance/access, DataZone for discovery/sharing portal"], correct:2, exp:"Amazon DataZone is purpose-built for data mesh: business data catalog (domain-specific), data product publishing workflow, subscription-based access (teams request access to data products), cross-account sharing, and a web portal for discovery. Lake Formation provides the underlying governance (fine-grained access control). For a data mesh specifically, DataZone provides the organizational/publishing layer that Lake Formation alone doesn't offer.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company runs EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling group. They need to ensure that during a scale-in event, the instance with the fewest active connections is terminated first (to minimize user disruption). Which ASG feature controls this?", opts:["Default termination policy (terminates oldest launch config first)","Custom Termination Policies — select 'ClosestToNextInstanceHour' or create a custom scale-in protection strategy. For connection-based: enable connection draining on ALB + use scale-in protection on instances with active connections.","Scale-in protection on all instances (prevents any scale-in)","Lifecycle hooks to check connections before termination"], correct:3, exp:"ASG doesn't have a built-in 'fewest connections' termination policy. Approach: (1) Enable ALB connection draining (deregistration delay) — gives active connections time to complete. (2) Use a lifecycle hook on termination — a Lambda function checks connection count and can abandon the termination (keeps the instance) or continue. (3) Alternatively, use scale-in protection via SDK on instances with active connections. The combination minimizes user disruption during scale-in.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Organizations with consolidated billing. Account A has $50,000 in EC2 usage and Account B has $30,000. The Organization qualifies for volume pricing tier discounts. How are the discounts applied?", opts:["Each account gets individual tier pricing based on their own usage","Usage from ALL accounts in the Organization is AGGREGATED for volume discount tiers — the entire Organization benefits from collective purchasing power","Only the management account gets volume discounts","Volume discounts only apply to Reserved Instances"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Organizations consolidated billing aggregates usage across ALL member accounts to determine volume pricing tiers. Example: S3 pricing tiers are based on total storage. If Account A has 40TB and Account B has 60TB, the Organization qualifies for 100TB tier pricing (cheaper per-GB rate). This applies to: S3, data transfer, EC2 (compute usage for Savings Plans), and other services with volume tiers. One of the key financial benefits of Organizations.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company needs to implement a message queue with messages up to 2GB in size (containing video processing instructions + embedded video data). SQS has a 256KB message size limit. What is the recommended approach?", opts:["Split messages into chunks under 256KB","Use the SQS Extended Client Library — stores the message payload in S3 and sends only a reference (S3 pointer) in the SQS message. Consumer retrieves from S3.","Use Kinesis instead (also has size limits)","Use Amazon MQ with larger message support"], correct:1, exp:"SQS Extended Client Library (Java) or similar pattern: the producer stores the large payload (>256KB, up to 2GB) in S3 and sends an SQS message containing only the S3 object reference. The consumer reads the SQS message, retrieves the payload from S3, and processes it. This is the AWS-recommended pattern for large message payloads. Transparent to application logic (the library handles S3 upload/download automatically). Message ordering and deletion semantics preserved.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses GuardDuty for threat detection. GuardDuty generates a finding: 'Recon:EC2/PortProbeUnprotectedPort' for an EC2 instance. What does this mean and what should they do?", opts:["An EC2 instance is attacking other instances","A port on the EC2 instance is being probed from the internet (potential reconnaissance by an attacker). Immediate action: review Security Group rules, close unnecessary open ports, and investigate if the instance has been compromised.","The instance has a virus","DNS exfiltration detected"], correct:1, exp:"'Recon:EC2/PortProbeUnprotectedPort' means GuardDuty detected external IP addresses probing an unprotected port on the instance (port is open in SG but has no protection like WAF). This is reconnaissance — attackers scanning for vulnerabilities. Response: (1) Review Security Groups — close unnecessary open ports, (2) Check if the port should be public, (3) Add WAF/NACL restrictions if the port must be open, (4) Investigate if any probe was successful (check VPC Flow Logs for established connections).", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon EFS with Standard storage class. 80% of files are accessed less than once per month. They want to reduce storage costs. What EFS feature helps?", opts:["EFS One Zone storage class (reduces availability, not access-based tiering)","EFS Lifecycle Management — automatically moves files not accessed for N days (7/14/30/60/90) to Infrequent Access (IA) storage class (up to 92% cheaper)","Delete old files manually","Compress files before storing (application-level, not EFS native)"], correct:1, exp:"EFS Lifecycle Management works like S3 Intelligent-Tiering: files not accessed within the configured period (7-90 days) automatically move to the EFS IA storage class (~$0.016/GB vs $0.30/GB Standard = 92% cheaper). When accessed, files are served from IA directly (slightly higher per-access cost). With 80% of files rarely accessed, cost reduction is approximately 80% × 92% = ~74% total storage cost reduction. Enable with one setting change — no application modifications.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company builds a serverless application with API Gateway → Lambda → DynamoDB. They want to add request rate limiting per API key (e.g., free tier: 100 requests/day, premium: 10,000 requests/day). How is this configured?", opts:["Lambda function checks rate limits in DynamoDB","API Gateway Usage Plans with API Keys — define rate limits (requests/second) and quotas (requests/day) per plan, associate API keys with plans","CloudFront rate limiting","WAF rate-based rules per API key"], correct:1, exp:"API Gateway Usage Plans provide: (1) Throttling — requests/second and burst limit per plan, (2) Quotas — maximum requests per day/week/month per plan. Create plans: 'Free' (100/day quota) and 'Premium' (10,000/day quota). Generate API keys, assign each customer's key to the appropriate plan. API Gateway enforces limits automatically — returns 429 when exceeded. No custom code needed. This is the standard API monetization pattern on AWS.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company has an EC2 instance that needs to send emails. When the instance sends emails via SMTP (port 25), they are blocked. Why?", opts:["EC2 blocks port 25 for all instances to prevent spam","AWS restricts outbound SMTP (port 25) by default to prevent EC2 from being used as spam relays. Request removal of the restriction OR use Amazon SES (port 587/465) or a third-party SMTP relay on alternate ports.","Security Group blocks port 25 outbound (SGs allow all outbound by default)","The instance needs a special IAM permission for email"], correct:1, exp:"AWS throttles/blocks outbound port 25 (SMTP) on EC2 by default to prevent email spam. Solutions: (1) Request the restriction removal via AWS Support (must justify legitimate use). (2) Use Amazon SES for email sending (uses port 587 or API — not blocked). (3) Use a third-party SMTP service on port 587/465 (alternate submission ports aren't restricted). SES is the recommended approach for application email. Port 25 block is a common surprise for developers.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses AWS WAF with managed rule groups (AWS Managed Rules). They notice legitimate requests are being blocked by the SQL injection rule. How can they allow specific requests through while keeping SQL injection protection?", opts:["Disable the entire SQL injection rule group (removes protection)","Add a WAF rule with higher priority that explicitly ALLOWS the specific requests (by IP, path, or header) BEFORE the managed rule evaluates them. Or use scope-down statements to exclude specific paths from the managed rule group.","No way to override managed rules","Contact AWS to modify the managed rule"], correct:1, exp:"WAF rules are evaluated in order of priority. Solutions: (1) Add a higher-priority rule that allows specific requests matching certain criteria (IP, URL path, header value) — they pass through before reaching the managed rule. (2) Use scope-down statements on the managed rule group to EXCLUDE certain URLs from evaluation. (3) Set specific rules within the group to COUNT instead of BLOCK (logs but doesn't block). These approaches maintain protection while reducing false positives.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Redshift as their data warehouse. They want to query data stored in S3 WITHOUT loading it into Redshift (the data is too large to store fully in Redshift). Which Redshift feature enables this?", opts:["COPY command (loads data INTO Redshift — requires storage)","Redshift Spectrum — queries S3 data directly from Redshift using external tables (no loading needed, pay per TB scanned like Athena)","Redshift UNLOAD (exports FROM Redshift to S3 — wrong direction)","Federated Query (queries other databases, not S3)"], correct:1, exp:"Redshift Spectrum extends Redshift's query engine to S3. Create external tables (pointing to S3 locations via Glue Data Catalog or Redshift external schema), then query them with standard SQL — even joining S3 data with Redshift local tables. Only scans the S3 data needed ($5/TB). Perfect for querying historical data in S3 while keeping hot data in Redshift. No data loading, no Redshift storage consumed for external tables.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company stores encrypted data in S3 using SSE-KMS. A user with appropriate S3 permissions tries to download a file but gets 'Access Denied'. What is the MOST likely issue?", opts:["S3 encryption is preventing download","The user has S3 permissions but LACKS KMS permissions (kms:Decrypt on the KMS key used to encrypt the object). Both S3 and KMS permissions are required for SSE-KMS encrypted objects.","The bucket policy explicitly denies the user","The object ACL restricts access"], correct:1, exp:"SSE-KMS encrypted objects require BOTH: (1) S3 permission (s3:GetObject on the bucket/object) AND (2) KMS permission (kms:Decrypt on the CMK used for encryption). If the user's IAM policy only grants S3 permissions, they can't decrypt — resulting in AccessDenied. This is a common gotcha: granting S3 access isn't enough for KMS-encrypted objects. The KMS key policy must also allow the user/role. Two permission checks, both must pass.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company wants to create a landing page that can handle a massive viral traffic spike (from 0 to 10 million requests in minutes) with ZERO infrastructure management. The page is static HTML/CSS/JS. What is the simplest architecture?", opts:["EC2 Auto Scaling behind ALB (takes minutes to scale, might not handle 0→10M spike fast enough)","S3 static website hosting + CloudFront CDN (both infinitely scalable, fully managed, handles any traffic spike instantly)","Lambda@Edge generating HTML dynamically","ECS Fargate with auto-scaling"], correct:1, exp:"S3 + CloudFront: unlimited scalability with zero management. S3 handles virtually unlimited requests. CloudFront caches content at 400+ edge locations globally — most requests never reach S3. Static content is served from edge cache with single-digit millisecond latency. No scaling configuration needed, no servers, no warm-up time. Handles 0 to millions of requests instantly. This is THE architecture for static content at massive scale. Cost: a few dollars for 10M requests.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses AWS Config rules to check compliance. They have a rule ensuring all EC2 instances have detailed monitoring enabled. A developer launches an instance without it. What happens?", opts:["Config prevents the instance from launching (Config is detective, not preventive)","AWS Config evaluates the instance as NON_COMPLIANT. If auto-remediation is configured, it triggers an SSM Automation document to enable detailed monitoring. If not, it just reports non-compliance.","Config automatically enables detailed monitoring","Nothing — Config only checks at scheduled intervals"], correct:1, exp:"AWS Config is a DETECTIVE control — it evaluates compliance but does NOT prevent non-compliant resources from being created. When the instance launches without detailed monitoring: (1) Config evaluates it as NON_COMPLIANT, (2) If auto-remediation is configured, it triggers SSM Automation to fix it, (3) If not, it simply appears as non-compliant in the Config dashboard. For PREVENTION, use SCPs or IAM policies with conditions. Config detects + optionally remediates, it doesn't prevent.", domain:1},
  {q:"A company needs to run a SQL query that joins data from their RDS PostgreSQL database AND their DynamoDB table in a single query. Is this possible without ETL?", opts:["No — you can't join across different database engines","Yes — use Amazon Athena Federated Query with connectors for both RDS PostgreSQL and DynamoDB, query both with standard SQL in a single Athena query","Use Redshift Federated Query for RDS + Redshift Spectrum for DynamoDB (complex but works)","Copy all data to a single database first"], correct:1, exp:"Athena Federated Query uses data source connectors (Lambda-based) to query external data sources. Available connectors: RDS (MySQL, PostgreSQL), DynamoDB, Redshift, CloudWatch, and more. Write a single Athena SQL query that JOINs data from RDS and DynamoDB (each as an external catalog). No ETL, no data movement. Also: Redshift Federated Query can query RDS directly, and DynamoDB export to S3 enables Spectrum queries. Athena Federated Query is the most flexible.", domain:3},
  {q:"A company uses Elastic Beanstalk with a Docker platform. They want to deploy multiple containers per instance (sidecar pattern — application + log collector + monitoring agent). What Beanstalk configuration supports this?", opts:["Single-container Docker (only one container per instance)","Multi-container Docker using ECS (Dockerrun.aws.json v2) — OR the newer ECS-managed platform that uses docker-compose.yml to define multiple containers per instance","Deploy each container as a separate Beanstalk environment","Use Lambda instead of containers"], correct:1, exp:"Elastic Beanstalk ECS platform supports multiple containers per instance. Define containers in Dockerrun.aws.json v2 (ECS task definition format) or docker-compose.yml. Each instance runs all defined containers: application container + sidecar containers (logging, monitoring, etc.). Beanstalk manages the ECS cluster, task placement, and scaling. This enables the sidecar pattern without directly managing ECS infrastructure.", domain:2},
  {q:"A company uses Amazon Aurora Serverless v2 for a development database. They set minimum ACU (Aurora Capacity Units) to 0.5 and maximum to 8. The database is idle for 16 hours/day. They notice they're still paying during idle time. Is this expected?", opts:["No — Serverless should scale to zero when idle","Yes — Aurora Serverless v2 scales down to the minimum ACU but NOT to zero. It always consumes at least the minimum ACUs (0.5 ACU = still billed). Only Aurora Serverless v1 could pause to zero.","The database has a bug preventing scale-down","Reserved capacity is preventing scaling"], correct:1, exp:"Aurora Serverless v2 scales between min and max ACU but NEVER to zero. The minimum is 0.5 ACU (always running, always billed). Aurora Serverless v1 (now being deprecated) could pause to zero after inactivity. For dev/test databases that should cost zero when idle, consider: RDS with scheduled stop/start (via Lambda), or use v1 if still available. v2 is designed for production workloads that need instant scaling, not cost optimization for idle databases.", domain:4},
  {q:"A company uses CloudFormation and wants to update a stack but is worried the update might delete or replace critical resources (like an RDS database). How can they protect specific resources from being modified or deleted during updates?", opts:["Stack termination protection (protects entire stack from deletion, not individual resources from updates)","Stack Policy — a JSON document that defines which resources can be updated and what update actions are allowed. By default, allows all updates; you can deny Update:Replace and Update:Delete on specific resources.","DeletionPolicy: Retain on the resource (protects on stack delete but not during updates)","Resource-level condition in the template"], correct:1, exp:"Stack Policy controls which update actions are permitted on specific resources. Example: deny Update:Replace on your RDS instance — CloudFormation will FAIL the update if it requires replacing the database. This prevents accidental data loss from updates that would replace (delete + recreate) stateful resources. DeletionPolicy:Retain only applies when the stack is DELETED or resource is removed from template — not during updates. Stack Policy is the update-time protection mechanism.", domain:2},
]
